04648nam a22008055i 9780231542760DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016026230  a97802315427607 a10.7312/reed175742doi  a(DE-B1597)478153  a(OCoLC)979739691  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBH221.J3bR44 2017 4aBH221.J3bR44 2017 7aLIT0041602bisacsh04a111/.85092231 aReed, Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBachelor Japanists :bJapanese Aesthetics and Western Masculinities /cChristopher Reed. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (440 p.) :b95 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aModernist Latitudes00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tA Note on Names and Terms -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Originating Japanism: Fin-de-Siècle Paris -- t2. Bachelor Brahmins: Turn-of-the-Century Boston -- t3. Sublimation and Eccentricity in the Art of Mark Tobey: Seattle at Midcentury -- tConclusion: On the End of Japanism -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aChallenging clichés of Japanism as a feminine taste, Bachelor Japanists argues that Japanese aesthetics were central to contests over the meanings of masculinity in the West. Christopher Reed draws attention to the queerness of Japanist communities of writers, collectors, curators, and artists in the tumultuous century between the 1860s and the 1960s.Reed combines extensive archival research; analysis of art, architecture, and literature; the insights of queer theory; and an appreciation of irony to explore the East-West encounter through three revealing artistic milieus: the Goncourt brothers and other japonistes of late-nineteenth-century Paris; collectors and curators in turn-of-the-century Boston; and the mid-twentieth-century circles of artists associated with Seattle's Mark Tobey. The result is a groundbreaking integration of well-known and forgotten episodes and personalities that illuminates how Japanese aesthetics were used to challenge Western gender conventions. These disruptive effects are sustained in Reed's analysis, which undermines conventional scholarly investments in the heroism of avant-garde accomplishment and ideals of cultural authenticity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAesthetics, Japanese. 0aEast and West. 0aMasculinity in art. 0aMasculinity in literature. 0aQueer theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / LGBT.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063857808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2016z9783110485264oZDB-23-DKU40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/reed1757440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231542760423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231542760/original  a978-3-11-063857-8  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-064982-6  Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2016  aZDB-23-DKUb2016